---
import ScienceLayout from '../../layouts/ScienceLayout.astro';
import { Image } from 'astro:assets';

import toprakFig2 from '../../assets/images/science/toprak-2012-fig2.png';
import toprakFig4 from '../../assets/images/science/toprak-2012-fig4.png';
import ozFig1 from '../../assets/images/science/oz-2014-fig1.jpeg';
import ozFig3 from '../../assets/images/science/oz-2014-fig3.jpeg';
---

<ScienceLayout title="Morbidostat | Toprak Lab" description="Build your own morbidostat — an automated high-throughput fluidic system for studying bacterial drug resistance.">
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="morbidostat-intro">
        The morbidostat is an automated high-throughput fluidic system for studying bacterial drug resistance in dynamically sustained drug environments. By continuously adjusting antibiotic concentrations in response to bacterial growth, it maintains constant selective pressure — enabling direct, real-time observation of resistance evolution.
      </p>

      <div class="article-card">
        <span class="article-card__label">Protocol</span>
        <h2 class="article-card__title">Building a morbidostat: an automated continuous-culture device for studying bacterial drug resistance under dynamically sustained drug inhibition</h2>
        <p class="article-card__authors">E. Toprak*, A. Veres, S. Yıldız, J.M. Pedraza, R. Chait, J. Paulsson &amp; R. Kishony*</p>
        <p class="article-card__journal"><em>Nature Protocols</em> <strong>8</strong>, 555–585 (2013)</p>
        <div class="article-card__actions">
          <a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/nprot.2013.021" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="article-card__btn">View on Nature.com</a>
          <a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/nprot.2013.021.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="article-card__btn article-card__btn--secondary">Download PDF</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section section--alt">
    <div class="container">
      <h2 class="subsection-heading">Real-Time Observation of Resistance Evolution</h2>
      <p class="subsection-desc">
        The foundational morbidostat experiments revealing reproducible genetic trajectories.
      </p>

      <figure class="full-figure">
        <Image src={toprakFig2} alt="Resistance trajectories showing parallel populations evolving under chloramphenicol, doxycycline, and trimethoprim — stepwise vs smooth IC50 increases and normalized growth rate heatmaps" width={720} quality={95} densities={[1, 2]} />
        <figcaption>
          <strong>Parallel populations attain high resistance.</strong> Five replicate <em>E. coli</em> populations evolved under chloramphenicol, doxycycline, and trimethoprim show distinct resistance dynamics — trimethoprim resistance increases in discrete steps, while chloramphenicol and doxycycline resistance rises smoothly, reflecting different underlying mutational mechanisms.
          <span class="figure-source">Toprak, Veres, Michel et al., <em>Nature Genetics</em> (2012)</span>
        </figcaption>
      </figure>
      <figure class="full-figure">
        <Image src={toprakFig4} alt="DHFR crystal structure with color-coded resistance mutations, temporal pie charts tracking mutation fixation across 5 populations, and statistical reproducibility analysis" width={720} quality={95} densities={[1, 2]} />
        <figcaption>
          <strong>Semi-ordered acquisition of resistance mutations.</strong> Whole-genome sequencing reveals that the same DHFR mutations arise independently across replicate populations in a predictable order. The reproducibility of mutational trajectories is significantly higher than expected by chance, indicating that resistance evolution follows constrained genetic paths.
          <span class="figure-source">Toprak, Veres, Michel et al., <em>Nature Genetics</em> (2012)</span>
        </figcaption>
      </figure>

      <div class="article-card">
        <span class="article-card__label">Nature Genetics 2012</span>
        <h3 class="article-card__title">Evolutionary paths to antibiotic resistance under dynamically sustained drug selection</h3>
        <p class="article-card__authors">E. Toprak, A. Veres, J.B. Michel, R. Chait, D.L. Hartl, R. Kishony</p>
        <p class="article-card__journal"><em>Nature Genetics</em> <strong>44</strong>, 101–105 (2012)</p>
        <p class="article-card__summary">
          The first morbidostat experiments tracked <em>E. coli</em> evolving resistance to chloramphenicol, doxycycline, and trimethoprim in real time. Whole-genome sequencing revealed that resistance follows reproducible genetic trajectories — the same mutations arise independently across replicate populations, often in a predictable order.
        </p>
        <div class="article-card__actions">
          <a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/ng.1034" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="article-card__btn">View Article</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section section--alt">
    <div class="container">
      <h2 class="subsection-heading">Selection Strength Shapes Evolutionary Complexity</h2>
      <p class="subsection-desc">
        How the intensity of antibiotic pressure determines the genetic routes to resistance.
      </p>

      <figure class="full-figure">
        <Image src={ozFig1} alt="Experimental design comparing strong vs mild antibiotic selection in the morbidostat, with temporal resistance curves for streptomycin, spectinomycin, and doxycycline" width={720} quality={95} densities={[1, 2]} />
        <figcaption>
          <strong>Strong vs mild selection.</strong> Across 88 populations and 22 drugs, both strong and mild selection achieve similar final resistance levels — but the temporal dynamics differ. Strong selection (red) drives faster initial adaptation, while mild selection (black) follows more gradual trajectories.
          <span class="figure-source">Oz, Guvenek, Yıldız et al., <em>Molecular Biology and Evolution</em> (2014)</span>
        </figcaption>
      </figure>
      <figure class="full-figure">
        <Image src={ozFig3} alt="Cross-resistance network diagrams comparing strong vs mild antibiotic selection — denser network under strong selection indicates more pleiotropic effects" width={720} quality={95} densities={[1, 2]} />
        <figcaption>
          <strong>Cross-resistance networks.</strong> Strong selection produces denser cross-resistance networks than mild selection — strains evolved under intense drug pressure more frequently gain collateral resistance or sensitivity to other antibiotics, reflecting fundamentally different genetic routes to similar resistance endpoints.
          <span class="figure-source">Oz, Guvenek, Yıldız et al., <em>Molecular Biology and Evolution</em> (2014)</span>
        </figcaption>
      </figure>

      <div class="article-card">
        <span class="article-card__label">Molecular Biology and Evolution 2014</span>
        <h3 class="article-card__title">Strength of selection pressure is an important parameter contributing to the complexity of antibiotic resistance evolution</h3>
        <p class="article-card__authors">T. Oz, A. Guvenek, S. Yıldız, E. Karaboga, Y.T. Tamer, N. Mumcuyan, V.B. Ozan, G.H. Senturk, M. Cokol, P. Yeh, E. Toprak</p>
        <p class="article-card__journal"><em>Molecular Biology and Evolution</em> <strong>31</strong>(9), 2387–2401 (2014)</p>
        <p class="article-card__summary">
          By varying antibiotic concentration regimes across 88 populations and 22 drugs, this study showed that selection pressure strength is a key determinant of evolutionary outcome — strong and mild selection achieve similar final resistance, but through fundamentally different genetic routes with distinct cross-resistance profiles.
        </p>
        <div class="article-card__actions">
          <a href="https://academic.oup.com/mbe/article/31/9/2387/2925782" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="article-card__btn">View Article</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</ScienceLayout>

<style>
  .section {
    padding-block: 1.25rem;
  }

  .morbidostat-intro {
    max-width: 720px;
    margin-inline: auto;
    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
    font-size: var(--size-md);
    line-height: 1.7;
  }

  .subsection-heading {
    font-family: var(--font-heading);
    font-size: var(--size-xl);
    font-weight: 400;
    text-transform: none;
    letter-spacing: normal;
    color: var(--color-gray-900);
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
    max-width: 720px;
    margin-inline: auto;
  }

  .subsection-desc {
    font-size: var(--size-sm);
    color: var(--color-gray-600);
    line-height: 1.6;
    max-width: 720px;
    margin-inline: auto;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }

  .full-figure {
    max-width: 720px;
    margin-inline: auto;
    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
    border: 1px solid var(--color-gray-100);
    border-radius: 4px;
    overflow: hidden;
    background: var(--color-white);
  }

  .full-figure img {
    width: 100%;
    height: auto;
    display: block;
  }

  .full-figure figcaption {
    padding: 0.625rem 1rem;
    font-size: var(--size-xs);
    color: var(--color-gray-600);
    line-height: 1.5;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--color-gray-100);
    background: var(--color-white);
  }

  .full-figure figcaption strong {
    color: var(--color-gray-900);
  }

  .figure-source {
    display: block;
    margin-top: 0.375rem;
    font-size: var(--size-xs);
    color: var(--color-gray-300);
  }

  .article-card {
    max-width: 720px;
    margin-inline: auto;
    border: 1px solid var(--color-gray-100);
    border-radius: 4px;
    padding: 1.75rem 2rem;
  }

  .article-card__label {
    display: inline-block;
    font-family: var(--font-heading);
    font-size: var(--size-xs);
    font-weight: 600;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    color: var(--color-navy-light);
    margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
  }

  .article-card__title {
    font-family: var(--font-heading);
    font-size: var(--size-lg);
    font-weight: 400;
    line-height: 1.4;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
    color: var(--color-gray-900);
    text-transform: none;
    letter-spacing: normal;
  }

  .article-card__authors {
    font-size: var(--size-sm);
    color: var(--color-gray-600);
    margin-bottom: 0.25rem;
  }

  .article-card__journal {
    font-size: var(--size-sm);
    color: var(--color-gray-600);
    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
  }

  .article-card__actions {
    display: flex;
    gap: 1rem;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
  }

  .article-card__btn {
    display: inline-block;
    padding: 0.6rem 1.5rem;
    font-size: var(--size-sm);
    font-weight: 600;
    text-decoration: none;
    border: 1px solid var(--color-navy);
    color: var(--color-white);
    background-color: var(--color-navy);
    transition: background-color 0.2s, color 0.2s;
  }

  .article-card__btn:hover {
    background-color: var(--color-navy-light);
    border-color: var(--color-navy-light);
  }

  .article-card__btn--secondary {
    color: var(--color-navy);
    background-color: transparent;
  }

  .article-card__btn--secondary:hover {
    color: var(--color-white);
    background-color: var(--color-navy);
  }

  @media (max-width: 768px) {
    .article-card {
      padding: 1.5rem;
    }
  }
</style>
